article.description: Jimmy Jackson scored 23 points off the bench to lead five players in double figures as the Miami Heat  continued their postseason push with an 90-78 victory over the  Phoenix Suns.
article.headline: Heat cut playoff gap to half a game, and counting

images.name: Mourning_Alonzo 020312 inline
images.caption: Stephon Marbury and the Suns found precious little room to maneuver against the Heat.

article.linkText: Miami wins again, inches ever closer to playoffs
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Heat keep finding different heroes in their pursuit of a playoff spot. Reserve Jim Jackson stepped up just in time. Jackson scored 23 points to lead a balanced offense Tuesday night as the Heat won again in their late-season playoff push, beating the Phoenix Suns 90-78. Jackson, playing extra minutes because of an ankle injury to Kendall Gill, helped spark the Heat to their eighth win in the last 10 games. Miami, which closed to half-a-game from the final playoff spot in the East, is 21-7 since Jan. 14. "Our motivation is to get to where we want to be," Jackson said. "Tonight we emphasized playing well at home and taking care of our home court. Hopefully, this will spur us on to play even better." Phoenix, 4½ games behind Utah for the final playoff spot in the West, was in the first of a four-game Eastern road trip. The Suns have lost four straight on the road and four of their last six overall. "We could have done a lot of things better," Suns guard Stephon Marbury said. "We put ourselves in a hole early, and they just kept coming at us." Jackson, signed to a free-agent contract in December, played 34 minutes and made 10 of 13 shots. The 23 points were just one shy of his season high. Gill, who has started 30 games this season, left in the second quarter with an ankle bruise and did not return. Rod Strickland scored 20 points for Miami, Eddie Jones followed with 16 and Brian Grant added 14. Jackson more than made up for Gill's absence, as he also grabbed seven rebounds and made all three of his 3-point attempts. "You need two or three guys to come off the bench to help with scoring, defense and rebounding," Jackson said. "That's what makes a good team a better team, a great team." Added Heat coach Pat Riley: "Jimmy has played the second-most number of minutes other than Eddie (Jones). We want him on the court. He has the ability to score and he has been shooting the ball well from 3-point range. Jimmy was the catalyst tonight." The win allowed the Heat to avenge one of their worst defeats this season, a 108-74 blowout at Phoenix on Feb. 12. "They have more of a flow to their game now," Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said. "Everybody on that team knows what's expected of them, and they're playing better basketball. Plus, they're playing their trademark defense." The Heat, well-rested after two days off, shot 57 percent from the floor in the first half en route to a 46-33 halftime lead. Center Alonzo Mourning, who missed practice the day before with the flu, was 5-of-6 in the first quarter to help Miami open a 20-12 lead nine minutes into the game. Mourning finished with 13 points in 30 minutes. Trailing by 13 at halftime, the Suns rallied in the third quarter, using a 16-4 run to get to 50-49 on Shawn Marion's jumper. Miami built the lead back to 63-56 at the end of the period, aided by a 3-pointer by Jackson. The Heat pulled away midway through the final period, with Jones' reverse layup and Mourning's hook shot pushing the lead to 75-62 with 6:46 left. Marbury led the Suns with 19 points and Joe Johnson added 18. "We needed to start the first half the way we started the second half," Marion said. "Once we got down early, we spent the entire game fighting back. Maybe we just ran out of gas."

Game notes
Suns backup guard Dan Majerle, who played from 1996 until last year for the Heat, was given a thunderous ovation when he entered late in the first quarter. "Dan was one of the class guys to come into this league in a long time," Heat coach Pat Riley said of Majerle, who will retire after this season. "He played the game the way it should be played and added great value to the NBA." ... Miami improved to 5-23 lifetime against Phoenix, winning for only the third time at home. ... Mourning was hit with a flagrant foul for his one-arm takedown of Jake Tsakalidis in the second quarter. .. The 78 points were the second fewest by the Suns this season.
